FT  25 SEP 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ZINC moved into backwardation again on the LME in an otherwise routine
trading day for the base metals. Dealers said cash zinc closed Dollars 9.50
ahead of three-month metal, compared with a discount of Dollars 5 on
Wednesday. Although fears of an October squeeze have faded, the market will
remain susceptible to pockets of technical tightness. COPPER closed steady.
Chinese buying in the morning aided sentiment, and dips towards Dollars
2,380 for three-month metal are likely to encounter support. After the
close, news emerged that Peru's Tintaya copper mine unions have voted to
strike by 1 October. Three-month TIN prices continued to drift downwards
towards the Dollars 6,500 a tonne chart objective. London COCOA remained
under pressure from talk of Ivorian selling. 'With the calmer tone in the
currency markets we're finding the cocoa fundamentals are playing their part
again,' one dealer said. New York COTTON futures were sharply lower at
midday. One analyst said the bears continued to be in charge. 'The fact that
there is excess cotton in mainland China, and the uncertainty as to what
they are going to do with it, is hanging heavily over the world market.'
