<HEADLINE>
FT  25 SEP 92 / Major puts ERM membership on indefinite hold: Smith calls
Tory leader the 'devalued prime minister of a devalued government'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR put British membership of the European exchange rate mechanism
on indefinite hold yesterday in the face of a bruising onslaught at
Westminster on the disin-tegration of his economic strategy.
Speaking just hours before Mr David Mellor's departure from the cabinet
delivered a further blow to his embattled government, Mr Major said: 'I do
not believe that we shall be able to go back into the mechanism soon, or
into the same mechanism we left.'
A commanding parliamentary debut as Labour leader by Mr John Smith in the
emergency debate served notice on Mr Major that he faces a challenging time
in the Commons chamber over the next few years.
In a wounding attack Mr Smith declared Mr Major was now 'the devalued prime
minister of a devalued government'.
Mr Major's comments, confirming that domestic economic recovery is now the
government's first priority, brought an immediate surge in equity prices on
London's financial markets. The FT-SE 100 index closed up 40.7 at 2621.2.
The prime minister's speech followed a long debate at a full meeting of the
cabinet about the direction of economic and European policy.
An increasingly hawkish Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, insisted that the
cabinet drop its previous formula that the pound would be put back into the
system 'as soon as conditions allow', in favour of the demands for reform of
the ERM set out later by Mr Major.
Pro-European ministers such as Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry
secretary, and Mr Kenneth Clarke, the home secretary, wanted a firmer
commitment to re-entry. But they acknowledged that the recent turmoil in the
ERM had strengthened the chancellor's position.
Senior ministers said that Mr Major's phrasing meant Britain would probably
remain out of the system for at least six months and quite possibly for a
year or more.
Mr Lamont confirmed that view in a combative speech in which he launched a
sharp attack on Professor Helmut Schlesinger, the president of the
Bundesbank.
Using phrases that will exacerbate the rift between the British and German
authorities, but which won him loud applause from his own backbenches, Mr
Lamont blamed the Bundesbank for the final speculative attack on sterling.
The subsequent judgment offered by MPs on the most difficult speech of Mr
Major's career was that it was a brave performance in which he had held the
line.
Mr Lamont meanwhile had defused speculation about his immediate future.
But to the fury of Mr Major's Euro-sceptics, the prime minister reaffirmed
his commitment to ratification of the Maastricht treaty. In what the
pro-European cabinet ministers claimed as an important victory, the prime
minister declared there was no future for Britain as a 'sour, isolated
country off the mainland of Europe'.
The prime minister sought to negotiate the treacherous fault-lines in his
party over Europe by emphasising the setting of a new condition for
implementation of the agreement on European union.
Referring to next month's emergency summit of EC leaders, Mr Major said that
the Community would have to give substance to the notion enshrined in
Maastricht of subsidiarity - the devolution of decision-making to national
governments.
Under constant sniping from Tory Euro-sceptics, he emphasised his continuing
support for Maastricht, arguing that a British prime minister could not sign
an international treaty and then disown it.
Last night prominent Euro-sceptics claimed the signatures of more than 50
Tory MPs for a Commons motion declaring that the government should re-assert
national control of economic policy by keeping the pound permanently outside
the ERM. Half-a-dozen of them abstained in last night's vote to reinforce
the protest.
Mr Major did not spell out in detail the reforms of the exchange rate system
that the government would be seeking. But Mr Lamont emphasised the need for
a sustained fall in German interest rates.
Other proposed changes focus both on technical matters of intervention and
on the fundamental issue of sharing responsibility for changes in monetary
policy between strong and weak currency governments.
In an effort to reassure financial markets, Mr Major emphasised the
government's determination to stick to its public spending targets.
Mr Lamont will tell cabinet colleagues later today that meeting the Pounds
244.5bn target for next year will involve cuts in sensitive budgets across
Whitehall.
The cabinet committee charged with sharing out the resources will consider
plans for cash reductions in the health service budget, a squeeze on
discretionary benefits and large cuts in Whitehall's capital spending
programmes.
DEBATE ON ECONOMY
