<HEADLINE>
FT  25 SEP 92 / Mellor resigns after backbench support evaporates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DAVID Mellor resigned as national heritage secretary last night after
accepting finally that a summer-long onslaught by tabloid newspapers, and,
more recently, pressure from Conservative MPs, made it impossible for him to
remain in his job.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, accepted Mr Mellor's decision as
executive officers of the Conservative backbench 1922 committee met to
consider demanding Mr Mellor's resignation because of the damage he was
causing the government.
The announcement came less than 24 hours after Mr Mellor launched a
last-ditch attempt to salvage his career in a series of television
interviews in which he protested that he had been caught in 'a trial of
strength between the tabloids and the prime minister'.
But Mr Mellor had said he would step down if his remaining in the government
became an embarrassment to colleagues. As MPs returned to Westminster for
the emergency debate on the economy, it was clear his support on the Tory
backbenches was slipping away, with the 1922 executive preparing to act as
executioners. Sir Marcus Fox, 1922 Committee chairman, rang Mr Mellor
yesterday morning.
Mr Major, who invested much political capital in remaining loyal to Mr
Mellor during the summer, accepted the resignation with 'deep regret'. But
it appears he made little attempt to dissuade Mr Mellor.
The toppling of Mr Mellor - the first cabinet resignation apart from
reshuffles since Mr Major became prime minister - added to the air of
political crisis surrounding the government.
Mr Mellor was a close friend of Mr Major, and fellow football supporter, as
well as being responsible for a department created by the prime minister
after the general election. A successor is expected to be announced shortly.
Speculation last night centred on Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to
the Treasury, Mr Tristan Garel-Jones, foreign office minister, or Baroness
Blatch, education minister.
Mr Mellor telephoned Downing Street before 9am yesterday, saying he was
minded to resign. He met Mr Major before cabinet in the morning and spoke
again on the telephone afterwards. Mr Mellor also met Sir Norman Fowler,
Conservative party chairman, before handing his resignation letter to Mr
Major as the prime minister left the Commons after his speech on the
economy. Mr Mellor will make a Commons statement today.
In his letter, Mr Mellor said he had 'concluded that it is too much to
expect of my colleagues in government and in parliament to have to put up
with a constant barrage of stories about me in certain tabloid newspapers'.
On allegations that he had acted improperly in accepting a paid holiday in
1990 from Mrs Mona Bauwens, daughter of a Palestine Liberation Organisation
member, Mr Mellor wrote that he was glad Mr Major had 'been able to make
clear that . . . I have acted within the guidance on the conduct of
ministers'.
He also thanked Mr Major for deciding his 'folly' in becoming embroiled in
an affair revealed in July, 'did not warrant leaving the government'.
His resignation brought expressions of regret from prominent members of the
arts world.
'It is a thousand pities that his tenure as secretary of state for a
brand-new department, which was so full of promise, has been cut short in
such tragic circumstances,' said Lord Palumbo, chairman of the Arts Council.
Mr Peter Jonas, general director of English National Opera, said: 'It is a
tragedy for the arts, for the country and the most unfair and cruel thing to
have happened to a man who was potentially the best secretary of state we
could ever have had.'
Mr Bryan Gould, Labour's national heritage spokesman who pressed the prime
minister over Mr Mellor's conduct, said it 'has become increasingly clear
that Mr Mellor was in breach of rules regarding ministerial conduct and that
has prevented him from carrying out his duties'.
But Mr Gould added that, 'in many ways today is a sad day for Britain's
cultural life'.
Mellor pays price, Page 8
Editorial Comment, Page 16
