FT  24 SEP 92 / International Company News: Two French food groups show
first-half increases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWO of the leading players in the French food industry, Eridiana Beghin-Say
and Saint-Louis, yesterday lightened the gloom in the French corporate
sector by announcing healthy increases in net profits for the first half of
the year.
Saint-Louis, with extensive interests in sugar and paper, saw net profits
rise by 30 per cent from FFr356m (Dollars 69.8m) in the first half of 1991
to FFr462m in the same period this year.
This increase includes the benefit of Saint-Louis' investment in Perrier,
the mineral water company which was the butt of a recent bid battle between
Nestle of Switzerland and the Agnelli family of Italy. Saint-Louis, which
sided with the Agnellis during the bid, took a stake in Perrier only to sell
it at a profit to Nestle.
Saint-Louis' sales rose from FFr5.32bn to FFr18.16bn and operating profits
from FFr365m to FFr719m because of the decision to consolidate its 39 per
cent stake in the Arjo Wiggins Appleton paper group.
Eridiana, also a significant player in sugar representing the restructured
food interests of Ferruzzi of Italy, saw net profits rise from FFr464m to
FFr572m in the first six months of 1992. It sees a 'similar rate of growth'
for the full year.
Operating profits rose 24 per cent to FFr1.67bn and sales by 22 per cent to
FFr24.1bn, reflecting the contribution of recent acquisitions such as
Ducros, the spice company.
