<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 92 / Banks reject Canary Wharf plan: Creditors may have to
provide Pounds 170m for Jubilee line extension
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANKERS to the troubled Canary Wharf development have rejected proposals for
taking over control of the east London property project from a group of US
investors which includes Mr Larry Tisch, the billionaire investor and Mr
Lewis Ranieri, the investment banker.
The proposal had been seen by some bankers as the only promising prospect of
progressing the development. The banks' decision appears to end hopes of
them securing outside capital for a vital private sector contribution to the
costs of extending the Jubilee Underground line, which is crucial to Canary
Wharf's prospects.
The project's bankers will now have to decide in the next few days whether
they themselves will provide the Pounds 170m needed.
According to bankers gathered in Washington for the annual meeting of the
International Monetary Fund, Canary Wharf's 11 leading bank creditors voted
by 7 to 4 to reject the proposal, which had been handled through Smith
Barney, the New York investment bank.
The group was formed by Mr Paul Reichmann, founder of the east London
development. A spokesman for Mr Reichmann last night put a brave face on the
decision, saying: 'There have been a series of discussions and the group is
hopeful that these discussions can continue'.
Lloyds Bank, the UK clearer, led opposition to the consortium proposal,
which was championed mainly by Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce.
Some banks opposed the bid because it would have left Mr Reichmann with an
equity interest in the project, and they blame him for their losses on loans
to the project.
The group, which was proposing to inject between Pounds 235m and Pounds 350m
into Canary Wharf, would have provided the first tranches of a private
sector contribution to the Jubilee costs. The UK government insists the
Jubilee extension to Canary Wharf and other parts of east London will not be
built unless it receives a firm commitment on a private sector contribution
by the end of the month.
The extension is seen as essential to attract tenants and save the banks
from huge losses on the Pounds 576m they lent to Canary Wharf. The banks are
considering proposing to the government that if it rented space at Canary
Wharf, the banks would refinance the buildings let to the government and
pass the funds back as a Jubilee contribution.
The administrators to the project, three partners of accountancy firm Ernst
&amp; Young appointed in May under UK insolvency legislation, want to put a
proposal to the government in the next few days.
Chemical Bank deserts Canary Wharf, Page 11
</TEXT>
