<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 92 / Councils warn on budget cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERS of local authorities yesterday renewed threats of wide-scale
redundancies to come if next year's grant settlement is, as expected, capped
at the rate of inflation or below and councils are not allowed to spend
their capital reserves.
The threats were given substance by an announcement by Sheffield City
Council that deep cuts, necessitating up to 800 redundancies, would be
needed to balance the ciy's budget.
Sheffield needs to save about Pounds 7.25m to keep spending down to about
Pounds 400m. The council's Labour leadership yesterday rejected suggestions
that it had deliberately overbudgeted, hoping to be rescued by a Labour
victory in the general election, but said that government limits for
continuing a normal range of services were too tight.
The city employs about 27,000 people, equivalent to 25,000 full-timers. Its
management standards have in the past been commended by the District
Auditor, the government's local watchdog on public spending.
The cuts package will be put to a council meeting on Monday. About 150 jobs
will go across all departments, plus 225 in works, cleansing and cleaning.
Some public toilets will be closed. Other cuts will affect book purchases by
libraries, council house maintenance and school clothing grants to parents
in need.
Mr Jeremy Beecham, chairman of the Labour-controlled Association of
Metropolitan Authorities, urged ministers to allow local authorities to
spend accumulated capital receipts to boost employment.
He said: 'English councils have about Pounds 7.2bn of accumulated capital
receipts, largely from the sale of council homes. But we can spend about
Pounds 700m of this because of government dogma that use of such receipts
increases the public-sector borrowing requirement.'
Local authorities are particularly concerned at shortfalls in funding for
community care of the elderly and disabled, for which councils will take
responsibility next April.
</TEXT>
