FT  24 SEP 92 / Smiths Industries buys medical group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SMITHS INDUSTRIES, the UK-based aerospace electronics, medical systems and
specialised industrial components group, is buying Intertech Resources, a
privately held US disposable medical products company, for Dollars 110m
(Pounds 64.3m).
Smiths' share price fell 6p to close at 308p.
The cash purchase, which includes the assumption of Dollars 18m debt, will
significantly expand Smiths' existing medical products business, while also
adding to the group's US operations. Smiths' is one of the world's leading
suppliers of disposable medical products and has significant market shares
in Europe, the Middle East and Asia.
Intertech is a large supplier of 'single-use' anaesthesia and respiratory
devices used in surgery and intensive care. It reported an operating profit
of Dollars 8m before interest of Dollars 1.6m on sales of Dollars 43.5m in
the year to June 30. It ended the period with assets of Dollars 24.4m.
Commenting on the acquisition Mr Roger Hurn, Smiths' chairman, said:
'Intertech is a strong company with highly respected brands. I expect the
company to make an early contribution to profits after financing costs.'
Smiths, which had net cash of Pounds 95m at the beginning of February, had
been expected to continue diversifying from defence and civil aerospace. Mr
Hurn hinted at an acquisition in April when he told analysts that the
group's management was ready for 'a major challenge'.
Intertech employs 450 people. Its headquarters are in Chicago, but its main
operations are in Fort Myers, Florida. Almost 90 per cent of its sales are
derived from its own production and its products are sold in the US
healthcare market directly and through distributors.
The acquisition, subject to US anti-trust clearance, will boost Smiths'
growing Medical Systems division which had sales of Pounds 125.3m in the
1990-91 financial year. In the latest six-month period to February 1 the
division accounted for 31 per cent of the group's Pounds 37.8m trading
profits and 21 per cent of its Pounds 307.4m half-year turnover.
The US company will join Smiths' existing medical operations in North
America which include disposable devices for intensive therapy, blood gas
sampling kits, and monitors for body temperature.
