<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 92 / Lecturers face tight limit on pay: Patten tells universities
to improve productivity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN PATTEN, education secretary, yesterday gave universities a sharp
warning that the expansion of student numbers will require tight limits on
lecturers' pay and the squeezing of more from existing resources.
'Any irresponsible increases in pay would lead not to an increase in
exchequer grant but to a loss of jobs,' he told vice-chancellors at their
annual meeting in Exeter. He added: 'The only prudent basis for an increase
in pay therefore is improvement in productivity and performance . . . I hope
there will be maximum scope for individual institutions to settle the pay of
their own staff locally within the resources available to them.'
After his action in overriding the vice-chancellors' 7 per cent pay offer to
lecturers earlier this year, Mr Patten's warning is tantamount to an
instruction. He said there was 'no other way' than continued efficiency
gains to ensure expansion towards the government's target of one in three
18-year-olds proceeding to higher education by the year 2000.
Mr Patten also urged vice-chancellors to give students with vocational
qualifications - particularly the General National Vocational Qualifications
being piloted this year - parity of treatment with A Level candidates in the
competition for places.
'The expectations of students will only be satisfied if higher education in
general is seen to be making a positive response,' he said, adding: 'Before
long it will not make sense to deal with higher-education entry on a basis
which presumes a standard A Level route.'
Mr Patten welcomed the decision of the Higher Education Funding Council for
England to review the organisation of the academic year.
Also addressing the vice-chancellors, Professor Graeme Davies, chief
executive of the funding council, reinforced the government's message on
efficiency. He said the funding council had asked Mr Patten to start
discussions with the Environment Department about planning restrictions that
limited expansion, and with the Treasury on the issue of universities using
premises as security for commercial loans. Universities are limited in their
capacity to use state-funded assets as security.
