<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 92 / Perot edging towards campaign decision
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR ROSS PEROT may decide next week whether or not to revive his abandoned
campaign for the US presidency, and on what basis.
The Texas billionaire, who said on Tuesday that he had made a mistake by
withdrawing from the race in July, has tentatively scheduled a meeting next
week with the heads of his volunteer movement in the various states. He says
he will take their advice. Several of them have publicly urged him to get
back into the contest.
Mr Perot also met privately on Tuesday Mr James Baker, who runs President
George Bush's campaign, and Mr Ron Brown, chairman of the Democratic
national committee. No report of either meeting has been forthcoming.
Perhaps the best insight into Mr Perot's thinking was provided in an
interview yesterday with the Washington Post by Mr James Squires, the former
Chicago newspaper editor who served as press secretary to Mr Perot's earlier
effort and is still on his payroll.
Mr Squires, who said he had spoken to Mr Perot several times over the
weekend, repeated that the latter wanted to continue to put pressure on Mr
Bush and on Governor Bill Clinton, the Democratic presidential candidate, to
come up with credible plans to cut the US budget deficit.
But, Mr Squires added: 'I don't think there is a chance in hell that Ross
Perot could ever endorse George Bush.' He could back Mr Clinton, if the
Democrat were to adopt some of Mr Perot's budget-cutting ideas, and he could
launch a limited campaign, confining himself to such states as Texas and
Florida, 'just to help Clinton,' Mr Squires believes.
Mr Perot insists he does not want to re-enter the race as 'a spoiler', and
he denies, as many suspect, that this renewed teasing of the political
process is mostly designed to satisfy his own ego.
Opinions are divided over the impact of his return, if any. It might
initially hurt Mr Clinton, because he was the principal beneficiary of the
July withdrawal, but hard-core Perot support is beyond dispute mostly
Republican.
In Florida and Texas, that support could, if energised, work to Mr Clinton's
favour; in the industrial Midwest, now leaning towards the Democrats, it
might cut the other way. In California, where Mr Perot was popular, Mr
Clinton now seems too far ahead to be threatened.
If he does return to the race, Mr Perot might claim a place at the televised
debates between the main candidates, assuming at least one takes place. The
Clinton and Bush campaigns continued yesterday to accuse each other of
conspiracy to prevent this confrontation.
But, if Mr Clinton's lead (21 points in the latest Washington Post/ABC
opinion poll) continues to hold up, the president may have no choice but to
accede to a debate.
However, the president's campaign, reflecting Mr Baker's thinking, continues
to maintain that Mr Clinton has most to gain by appearing on the same
platform as the president in a debate. It therefore rejected the latest
proposal by the independent commission in charge of the debates that one be
held at Louisville, Kentucky, next Tuesday with a single moderator rather
than a panel of questioners, as the Bush campaign wants.
The movement behind Mr Perot has at its hub the Perot Relations Committee,
constituted to put his name on all state ballots. According to the federal
election commission, Mr Perot has spent about Dollars 16m of his own money
on this effort - nearly Dollars 7m of that after his official withdrawal
from the race.
There is an almost complete absence of professional political advice and
polling in this volunteer organisation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
