FT  24 SEP 92 / International Company News: Allied-Signal to sell 39% stake
in Union Texas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALLIED-Signal, the industrial technology company in the throes of a major
restructuring, announced yesterday that it would be selling its 39 per cent
stake in Union Texas Petroleum in a public offering which is likely to raise
around Dollars 600m gross.
It will raise a further Dollars 355m through the cash redemption of Dollars
200m of preferred Union Texas shares and Dollars 155m of warrants. A
spokesman for Allied said the proceeds should translate into a pre-tax gain
of about Dollars 350m.
Mr Lawrence Bossidy, who took over as chairman of Allied in the summer of
1991, has made no secret of his desire to shed the company's oil and gas
interests as part of a slimming and refocusing of the high technology
conglomerate.
However, until now Allied had deemed the market for energy properties too
weak to justify a sale. The company said yesterday the proceeds would be
used to reduce debt, accelerate productivity improvements and for other
corporate purposes.
Costs associated with the productivity action might offset the gains from
the sale.
Union Texas is the second largest independent US oil company and is
particularly active in the UK and Indonesia.
It was acquired by Allied, then primarily a chemicals company, in 1962. In
1985 it went through a leveraged buy-out in which Kohlberg, Kravis Roberts,
the buy-out specialist, acquired a 50 per cent stake, and a public offering
followed in 1987.
A spokeswoman for KKR said yesterday it would be retaining its remaining 39
per cent equity stake, but would be redeeming Dollars 145m of warrants.
The Allied offer, expected to be completed in the fourth quarter, is for
33.3m shares of common stock.
