FT  24 SEP 92 / Barratt urges further interest rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR LAWRIE BARRATT, one of Britain's best-known housebuilders, yesterday
called on the government to cut interest rates to 6 per cent and introduce
other incentives to help the UK housing market, which remained in a deep
recession.
Sir Lawrie, chairman of Barratt Developments, was called out of retirement
14 months ago to rescue the company after it incurred an annual loss of
Pounds 105.9m.
Yesterday the group said it had made a pre-tax profit of Pounds 11.3m for
the 12 months to the end of June.
Sir Lawrie said in a letter to the prime minister and the chancellor, that
much more needed to be done if the housing market was to recover.
He contrasted the higher unemployment rate in Britain with that of the US,
which was also suffering from high trade and budget deficits.
'A bold approach must be taken to effect a major reduction in interest rates
more akin to the primate rate of 6 per cent prevailing in the US,' he wrote.
He also appealed for a permanent end to stamp duty on house sales which he
termed an 'iniquitous tax on home ownership'. He said: 'If it was right to
remove this tax in December last year to stimulate the housing market, then
it is even more essential to remove it again following the deterioration
which has taken place in the housing market since then.'
Sir Lawrie also called for the ceiling for mortgage tax relief to be raised
from Pounds 30,000 to more than Pounds 50,000.
He compared the failure to raise the tax allowance ceiling since 1983 with
increases in MPs' salaries during that time of 102 per cent and increases in
MPs' allowances of 225 per cent.
'The same treatment should be given to all homeowners entitled to mortgage
tax relief,' Sir Lawrie said.
He also called for a restoration of capital allowances to help the private
rented housing sector, which had fallen to just 7 per cent of the UK housing
stock.
Barratt results, Page 23
</TEXT>
