<DOCNO>FT923-1264</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIXB5AA7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920924
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 92 / More join ranks of the enemy within: The groundswell of
Conservative opinion against the Maastricht treaty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NO WONDER prime minister John Major has been adopting a Euro-sceptic tone of
late.
When he stands up to open today's emergency Commons debate on the
government's economic policy, he will be more conscious than ever of the
enemy within. It is the Conservative MPs who hold extreme doubts about the
text of the Maastricht treaty. As he weighs whether or not he can push the
treaty through parliament, Mr Major will be all too aware that the doubters'
ranks are growing.
A straw poll by the FT of Tory backbench opinion indicates that the number
of MPs prepared to defy the government, if it pushes for the Maastricht
treaty to be ratified without significant additions or amendments, has risen
to at least 40.
When the bill ratifying the treaty received its second Commons reading with
a majority of 244 four months ago, 22 Tories voted against the government.
Those who supported the government in May, but now say they could not back
the bill on the Maastricht treaty if it returned to the Commons unamended,
include: Sir George Gardiner, MP for Reigate; Mr Geoffrey Dickens,
Littleborough and Saddleworth; Mr Michael Lord, Suffolk Central; Mr John
Wilkinson, Ruislip-Northwood; Mr Andrew Hargreaves, Birmingham Hall Green;
Mr John Whittingdale, Colchester South and Maldon; Mr John Townend,
Bridlington; Mr Peter Griffiths, Portsmouth North; and Mr Michael Fabricant,
Mid Staffordshire.
In addition, Mr Roger Moate, MP for Faversham, who abstained on the second
reading, said he would now vote against unless there were 'enormous
amendments', while Mr Roger Knapman, MP for Stroud, who also abstained, said
he would not support the treaty 'in anything like its present form'.
The analysis - compiled from direct contact with a large number of Tory MPs
 -showed a wide divergence of opinion. Discontent with the text of the
treaty has increased markedly. But there were still those who saw no
difficulty either with the treaty or the government's ability to have it
ratified.
'I have no qualms about it whatsoever,' said Mr Robert Adley, MP for
Christchurch. 'I think the prime minister has a substantial majority in
favour across the parties.'
In addition to the 40 or more potential rebels, there was a sizeable
grouping of MPs who admitted to misgivings and stopped well short of
pledging unconditional support.
'If there is any thought of bulldozing through the same thing again, they
will find a lot of people like me hesitating,' said Mr James Hill, MP for
Southampton Test. Mr Nigel Waterson, MP for Mr Ian Gow's old seat of
Eastbourne, said: 'They cannot necessarily count on my support.'
A further sobering feature for the government was the number of MPs elected
for the first time at the general election in April who are among the most
sceptical. Many of those signed the motion in June that called on the
government to 'make a fresh start with the future development of the EC' in
the wake of the Danish referendum.
Most of those with reservations focused on the centralisation of powers and
the process of economic and financial integration. Backing for a single
European market was all but unanimous.
On centralisation, many MPs called for a clearer definition of the concept
of subsidiarity as set out in the treaty. The trouble with the present
definition was that 'you could drive a coach and horses through it',
according to Mr Fabricant, who said he would vote against ratification of
Maastricht 'as it stands at present'.
On financial integration, disillusioned MPs urged either extensive ERM
reform or recognition that the system was dead.
'I don't want us to go back into the ERM, so I don't see how I can support
Maastricht as it is,' said Mr Townend, chairman of the Tory backbench
finance committee. Sir Rhodes Boyson, a former minister, said: 'Any party
who say after this we are going back into the ERM should be consigned to
Devil's Island.' Circumstances would have to be 'very strange' for him to
support the Maastricht treaty if it returned to the Commons unamended.
Some MPs argued that the fault with the bill lay less in the text than the
government's failure to outline adequately what the treaty said. 'It is not
what is in Maastricht but what people think is in it,' said Mr Roger Sims,
MP for Chislehurst.
Many of the most sceptical prefaced their remarks by emphasising they were
not in the anti-European camp. Mr Griffiths said opposition was now coming
from 'committed Europeans' unhappy with the structures being proposed.
There was a common view among Euro-sceptics that they had supported the
government on the bill's second reading as a vote of thanks to Mr Major and
foreign secretary Douglas Hurd for negotiating UK opt-outs on the social
chapter and monetary union.
Some were also influenced by the assumption - since dispelled - that their
reservations would not be shared by significant numbers in other member
countries. 'One swallowed the bits one didn't like on the assumption the
rest of Europe was mad keen to go along,' according to one experienced MP,
who said Maastricht was now 'holed under the water'.
Mr Dickens said: 'It is nice to think we are not the only nation whingeing.'
There were several calls for a British referendum, although others were just
as passionately against such a step. A further group said the appropriate
time for a referendum would be prior to any decision to opt into a single
currency. Euro-enthusiast Mr Spencer Batiste, MP for Elmet, said: 'If there
is to be a referendum, it should be when the option on a single currency is
exercised.'
</TEXT>
