<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 92 / Labour split on Europe is staved off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday managed to avoid an open frontbench split over Europe
before today's critical Commons debate on the government's economic policy.
The party's ruling national executive committee rejected a referendum on
Maastricht, but many in the party believe that a showdown between Mr Bryan
Gould, shadow heritage secretary and a leading Labour Euro-sceptic, and Mr
John Smith, party leader, has been postponed rather than averted.
Mr Gould abstained in the NEC vote which approved by 24-2 a new policy
statement about economic and political co-operation in Europe. Earlier in
the meeting he joined Mr Tony Benn in supporting unsuccessfully a call from
Mr Dennis Skinner for a referendum on the Maastricht treaty and the UK's
withdrawal from the European exchange rate mechanism.
The leadership's uncompromising stance was seen in the rejection, by 22
votes to six, of a proposal from Mr David Blunkett - who ran Mr Gould's
failed campaign for the Labour leadership - that the party leave itself some
leeway on holding a referendum. At a separate meeting later, however, five
of the 20-plus shadow cabinet members expressed at least some sympathy with
the idea of a referendum.
The policy statement agreed yesterday confirms Labour's support for 'a
managed system of fixed but adjustable exchange rates, agreed through
international co-operation', and calls for stronger European action to
reduce currency speculation.
The paper also reaffirms the party's commitment to the UK's being at the
heart of Europe, pledging that Labour 'will continue to set out a positive
agenda for the devel-opment of the Community'.
Mr Gould is said to have been unhappy with the pro-European tone of the
statement.
The trigger for any possible split may come when the party decides what
tactics to adopt over the Maastricht bill. The shadow cabinet agreed
yesterday to remain silent on its approach to the legislation until the
government position is clearer.
Mr Smith reminded the shadow cabinet that while he had allowed public debate
on the party's attitude towards Europe in the run-up to yesterday's
meetings, the normal rules of collective responsibility would apply now that
decisions had been taken.
But Ms Clare Short, a 'soft-left' NEC member, said the paper did not
represent an end to discussion on the issue. 'It is still open season for
intelligent debate,' she said.
The first real test of whether Mr Gould intends to abide by the new policy
statement will be his appearance this morning at a press conference to
publish a pamphlet critical of the leadership's stance. Further indications
will come next week, when he will appear at several fringe meetings at the
Labour party conference in Blackpool - including, on Sunday, the
Euro-sceptic Common Market Safeguards Committee.
Meanwhile, the leadership was aiming to play down the significance of
articles to be published in two leftwing papers this morning, in which Mr
Gould returns to the attack on the Maastricht treaty. Officials pointed out
that the pieces were written before yesterday's meetings.
In New Statesman and Society Mr Gould describes the accord as 'a totally
overt, not to say shameless, statement of the bankers' view' of Europe while
in Tribune he warns against 'the establishment' in words that will be widely
read as a fierce attack on Mr Smith.
</TEXT>
