<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 92 / Bleak prospect for rural employment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 150,000 rural jobs may be lost in the 1990s as a result of a
contraction in agriculture and industries that depend on farming, the Rural
Development Commission said yesterday.
The commission, which promotes rural development, says in its annual report
that the 'peace dividend' resulting from a contraction of defence resources
will also lead to job losses, especially in East Anglia - where nearly 2 per
cent of the population is US forces personnel and families - and the
south-west of England.
It says an estimated 14,000 families are homeless in rural areas and
homelessness is growing faster than in towns.
Rural services and facilities are under continued pressure, with a number of
village halls threatened by the cost of complying with new hygiene and
safety regulations.
Lord Shuttleworth, the commission chairman, says in his annual review that
the nature of the changes taking place in the countryside are still
insufficiently recognised.
The countryside cannot be maintained by denying change or ignoring the needs
of country people, he adds.
The report says employment in small business grew faster in remoter rural
areas between 1988 and 1991 than anywhere else in England but the recession
means many businesses are now struggling for survival.
The commission plans to expand its social programmes by more than 20 per
cent over the next three years.
It will provide funds to create land banks to speed the supply of
inexpensive housing, give grants to help village halls meet the costs of new
health legislation, and help national charities extend their services into
rural areas.
It is working on its Countryside Employment Programme to help to create new
businesses and jobs in three pilot areas suffering badly from job losses.
The commission has also expanded a programme to convert redundant farm
buildings. RDC, 141 Castle Street, Salisbury, Wiltshire, SP1 3TP. Tel. 0722
336255. Pounds 13.50.
</TEXT>
