<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 92 / Fed 'not pressed to relax policy'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE White House yesterday denied reports that it had sought a private
undertaking from Mr Alan Greenspan, Federal Reserve chairman, to relax
monetary policy last year as a condition for his appointment to a second
term.
Mr Marlin Fitzwater, chief White House spokesman, said senior administration
officials had often called publicly for lower interest rates, but he denied
pressure was applied in private meetings. That would be inappropriate, he
said.
The denial followed a claim on Wednesday in the Los Angeles Times that the
administration had privately pressed Mr Greenspan 'for a commitment to pump
up the economy during 1992.'
The Fed was set up as an independent agency to prevent political control of
interest rate policy.
The newspaper said senior officials had held meetings with Mr Greenspan in
spring and summer last year to urge him 'to alter Fed policy in an effort to
reach specific growth targets during the coming election year.'
A Fed spokesman said Mr Greenspan had never committed the Fed to specific
economic growth targets.
Reuter reports: The US economy is improving slowly and prices are generally
stable, aside from a jump in lumber costs caused by Hurricane Andrew last
month, the Federal Reserve said in its latest national survey.
'Economic activity has been improving slowly in most of the nation, but the
pace of recovery has been uneven across regions and sectors,' the survey by
the 12 Federal Reserve banks said.
The report, known as the Beige Book, was based on information gathered
before September 15 and is the last one before the November 3 presidential
election, in which joblessness and economic weakness will be large in
voters' concerns.
</TEXT>
