<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 92 / UK, US to meet on air liberalisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH and US negotiators will meet early next month in a bid to speed up
talks on a new and more liberal air transport treaty.
Mr John MacGregor, the British transport secretary, met his US opposite
number, Mr Andrew Card, in Washington yesterday, and the two agreed to
accelerate the renegotiation of the 15-year old Bermuda II treaty which at
present regulates air traffic between the two countries.
The issue has been given added urgency by British Airways' proposal to take
a 44 per cent equity stake in USAir with a Dollars 750m (Pounds 438m)
investment, a proposal which must be approved by Mr Card.
Mr MacGregor insisted in Washington yesterday that the issues of
cross-border investment and air traffic liberalisation were entirely
separate. He pledged that, if the BA/USAir deal were approved, he would 'be
disposed to approve' a similar minority investment by a US airline in a UK
airline, but declined to tie the deal to freer access to British airports.
US air carriers, however, are not enthusiastic at the prospect of buying one
of the UK's small carriers; they want the British Airways deal to be linked
to removal of restrictions on capacity, gateways and pricing, allowing them
much broader opportunities to compete on European routes.
'Failure to require liberalisation of the existing air services agreement
with the UK prior to approving a BA investment in USAir would permit an
illiberal trading partner to obtain access to the US market without opening
its own markets to competition from US carriers,' said Mr Daniel Kasper,
director of the transportation practice at Harbridge House, a Boston
management consultancy.
</TEXT>
