<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / BAe to retain corporate jet division
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Aerospace yesterday announced it would retain its corporate jet
business, reversing an earlier decision to sell a majority stake in this
profitable sector. The move came on the eve of the company's announcement of
its interim results.
The company apparently failed to secure a sufficiently attractive offer for
this business.
The City expects the company will report a trading loss of between Pounds
20m to Pounds 40m. In addition, it could write-off as much as Pounds 750m on
various problem areas, mainly its regional aircraft operations. Investors
are also braced for a possible dividend cut.
The company is also expected to sign a preliminary agreement with Taiwan
Aerospace on a joint venture on the future of its loss-making regional
aircraft business.
Mr John Cahill, BAe's new chairman, is also due to unveil a radical
restructuring as part of the company's recovery strategy.
BAe's announcement that it would maintain control of corporate jet
activities was timed to coincided with the start of the Dallas business
aircraft trade show.
BAe said last May it was transferring its corporate jet business into a new
company called Corporate Jets with a view to selling a majority stake in
this activity. However, it said yesterday that, after reviewing several
proposals, it had decided it was in the best interests of shareholders,
customers and employees to retain the business.
Mr Dick Evans, BAe's chief executive, said yesterday he was pleased
uncertainty surrounding this activity had been lifted and 'we can now
concentrate . . on further improving our leading position in the market
place'.
BAe manufactures the 125-800 medium-sized twin-engined corporate jet and a
longer-range BAe 1000 at Chester with sales, design and engineering support
at Hatfield.
City analysts estimated the corporate jet business to be worth around Pounds
200m.
Beech Aircraft, the business aircraft subsidiary of Raytheon of the US, was
understood to have been interested in acquiring BAe's corporate business.
Dassault of France and Bombardier of Canada indicated this month they were
not interested.
Although the business continues to make money, BAe originally decided to
sell a controlling stake because of the substantial costs and risks of
developing future products.
</TEXT>
