<TEXT>
NALIN Industries, one of the biggest refiners of crude palm oil in Malaysia,
has been placed in receivership. Nalin, whose majority shareholder is the
Indian Birla merchant family, has been hit by tighter operating margins as
Malaysia's crude palm oil refining capacity has rapidly expanded in recent
years.
Malaysia's refineries now have a processing capacity of more than 10m tonnes
a year, though supply is only 6m tonnes. Nalin's total debt is estimated at
MDollars 100m (Dollars 40m).
