<DOCNO>FT923-1363</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIWCOADMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920923
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Tesco customers trading down in recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR IAN MacLaurin, chairman of Tesco, vigorously countered suggestions that
the grocery chain's newest stores were trading below expectation.
But he accepted that its customers were conspicuously trading down as a
result of the recession.
'We have opened 12 new stores this year and they are among the best we have
ever opened,' Sir Ian said when presenting Tesco's interim results
yesterday.
There was, however, widespread evidence of customers buying less expensive
foods.
'We have more customers in the younger age groups - between 25 and 40 - who
by and large have been affected worse by the recession than the senior
citizens,' he said.
Tesco intends to open 13 more stores in the second half, although its
opening programme is developing at a slower rate than mapped out at the time
of its Pounds 572m rights issue in February 1991.
Sir Ian said this reflected problems of winning planning approval at
individual sites rather than any change of policy. 'There is absolutely no
change in the strategic direction at all,' he said.
Tesco ended the period with 401 stores and trading area of 11m sq ft. Next
year it will add 900,000 sq ft of selling space.
Capital expenditure for the full year is expected to be about Pounds 730m.
During the half year the company spent Pounds 317m, of which Pounds 266m
went on new store developments.
Mr David Reid, finance director, said: 'Opening new stores in a recession is
a lot harder than before and the returns across the industry are coming down
a bit, but they can afford to come down.'
The company was also affected by the sharp fall in prices for many food
items. Over the past three half-year periods the grocery industry's
like-for-like sales increases have fallen from 4.1 per cent to 3.1 per cent
to 1.5 per cent. Price deflation for fruit and vegetables this summer was a
'staggering' 18 per cent, Sir Ian said.
The fall in the value of sterling may halt the deflationary pressures as 25
per cent of Tesco's goods are imported. However, the company does not expect
a rapid change in the position and has already bought-forward currencies
until Christmas.
Tesco noticed a sharp increase in the demand for multi-save items and
introduced a number of 'value lines' in many stores. However, sales of some
high-value lines such as sandwiches, fresh ready meals and champagne
increased substantially.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 23
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-1364</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIWCOADLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920923
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Next displays strong improvement to Pounds
8.3m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEXT, the fashion retailer, continued its recovery with a pre-tax profit of
Pounds 8.3m in the first half, compared with just Pounds 200,000.
The advance in the six months to July 31 came from slightly reduced turnover
of Pounds 212.6m (Pounds 219.7m) as the group further reduced its peripheral
activities. The figures were helped by Pounds 2m (Pounds 500,000) of
interest received.
Next again beat most expectations - as it did with its 1991-92 pre-tax
outcome of Pounds 12.3m - and the share price rose 3 1/2 p to close at 102
1/2 p.
Next Retail turned an operating loss of Pounds 1.9m into a Pounds 4.1m
profit. The result was struck on sales up from Pounds 125.1m to Pounds
138.4m. Lord Wolfson, chairman, said the high street stores, excluding
clearance, increased sales by 13.6 per cent.
The total number of shops fell from 348 to 316 under the policy of closing
loss-making outlets and rationalising neighbouring outlets. The clearance
operation was cut back to only six shops.
Mr David Jones, chief executive, said that strong stock control and 'short,
sharp' end-of-season sales had greatly reduced the surplus. The group had
traded for 23 of the 26 weeks without discounting.
Next Directory improved its operating profit to Pounds 2.7m (Pounds 1.4m),
on flat sales of Pounds 42.8m (Pounds 42.7m), through better control of
stock and other costs.
Excluding Club 24, the credit operation that has been one of Next's problem
areas, the amount of cash held rose to Pounds 114m, compared with Pounds
106m at the year-end. The balance sheet was restored last year through the
Pounds 167.5m disposal of Grattan, the mail order group.
Repayment of Eurobonds next month will take Pounds 87m cash.
Club 24, which at one stage had debt of more than Pounds 330m, contributed
Pounds 22.6m (Pounds 38.9m) to sales but had no impact on profits. Mr Jones
said the group was withdrawing from providing funds for the credit service
offered to other stores. Instead it would manage the accounts for a
commission.
By next year the switch should be complete, leaving core borrowings of about
Pounds 20m. Club 24 could then be brought back on to the balance sheet.
Meanwhile, about Pounds 10m of unused provisions would lead to an
exceptional credit in this year's accounts.
Earnings per share rose to 2.01p (nil). An interim dividend of 0.5p (nil) is
declared.
COMMENT
Next's customers - 'young women aged 18 to 80' as Lord Wolfson puts it  -
have given the shops the benefit of the doubt after the dark era, responding
nostalgically to the return of the old style. Hence its good performance in
a highly competitive market. Even more impressive is the resilience of the
men's wear side, which accounts for 30 per cent of sales. Some price
reductions and an embracing of the idea of popular appeal, rather than
exclusivity, have helped keep the men happy, while the former plethora of
women's lines has been rationalised. There is scope for further margin
improvement as the management sticks to its recovered knitting. Upgraded
profit forecasts of about Pounds 26m give a prospective p/e of more than 16,
on a 10 per cent tax rate that should last another couple of years. While
there is still some running in the recovery story, most of it is in the
share price.
</TEXT>
