<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / International Company News: Michelin's return to profit
fails to satisfy the bourse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MICHELIN, the world's largest tyre-maker, yesterday announced a turnround
approaching FFr2bn to report a net profit of FFr820m (Dollars 162m) in the
first half of the year against a FFr1.06bn loss a year earlier.
The improvement came mainly from savings following 11,400 job losses and a
reduction in stocks to 23 per cent of annual sales by the end of June (from
26 per cent of turnover a year earlier). Mr Eric Bourdais de Charbonniere,
finance director, said Michelin will have lost 16,000 jobs by the end of
this year, when the lay-offs will be complete.
The turnround was 'more than satisfying', he said, though all Michelin's
main competitors had also improved their performance this year. However, the
stock market had expected a bigger recovery, and Michelin's share price
price fell by FFr4.7 to FFr199.8 as analysts revised down their full-year
profit forecasts.
Michelin's improvement came on a sluggish tyre market, with volume sales up
by a mere 3 per cent. It managed to increase prices for replacement tyres in
the second quarter by between 3 per cent and 7 per cent in Europe and
slightly less in North America. Michelin does not divulge prices of new
tyres supplied to car-makers.
Group turnover rose by 5.6 per cent to FFr34.8bn from the first half of
1991, or by 8 per cent adjusting for currency changes, on which operating
costs were steady at FFr32.88bn. Mr Bourdais de Charbonniere said: 'For the
coming months, we continue to expect small growth in the world tyre market.'
The group had held its 20 per cent share of the world tyre market but lost
unspecified market share in North America because of the closure of two
out-dated factories belonging to Uniroyal Goodrich, the US tyre-maker which
Michelin bought two years ago. However, Michelin planned to increase
production capacity there to compensate, added Mr Bourdais de Charbonniere.
A capital increase this year could not be ruled out, but Mr Bourdais de
Charbonniere noted the stock market 'recently has not been encouraging'.
Michelin has in the past hinted that it would make a rights issue as soon as
its performance had recovered.
</TEXT>
