<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / UN burden too heavy, says Hurd
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations risks being saddled with too heavy a burden of
intervention and peace-keeping as the nations of the world were trying to
build a stronger system of collective security, Mr Douglas Hurd, the British
foreign secretary, told the United Nations General Assembly yesterday.
Mr Hurd, current president of the European Community's Council of Ministers,
said governments should realise that the new emphasis on collective
peace-keeping and peace-making would require restructuring of armed forces
and 'a massive increase' in the funds which the UN and its humanitarian
agencies would require from member states. Moreover, these new demands were
being made at a time when many member states faced severe budgetary
problems.
Expressing full support both for the ideas put forward by Mr Boutros Boutros
Ghali, the UN secretary-general, in his 'Agenda for Peace' earlier this
year, and US President George Bush's latest initiative to strengthen the
UN's peace-keeping work, Mr Hurd said that 'preventive diplomacy' was the
best way to deal with the world organisation's increasing work-load.
The UN secretary-general should be ready to make full use of his powers to
draw the attention of the Security Council to any matter which in his
opinion might threaten international peace and security. Greater use was
being made of fact-finding missions and the EC wanted to encourage this.
Mr Hurd said preventive deployment of troops might take place to deter
aggression or conflict between states.
Supporting Mr Boutros Ghali's proposal for a peace-keeping reserve fund, Mr
Hurd said that, at the end of August, the EC had provided 40 per cent of
contributions collected for various new peace-keeping operations since the
end of the last General Assembly.
Russia yesterday proposed installing 'hot-lines' between the world's
capitals and UN headquarters, regular intelligence briefings for the
secretary-general and greater use of fact-finding missions to enhance the
United Nations capacity to head off conflicts, Michael Littlejohns reports
from New York.
In a speech to the General Assembly, Mr Andrei Kozyrev, Russia's foreign
minister, said that when political means failed 'force may and should be
used' to separate the warring sides.
</TEXT>
