<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / Ford's short-time working extended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD, Britain's leading vehicle manufacturer, is to extend short-time
working at its three British assembly plants at least until the end of next
month in response to disappointing sales in the UK and weakening demand from
export markets.
It has also reduced output at its assembly plants at Saarlouis and Cologne
in Germany as well as its Spanish plant at Valencia, while extending
short-time working at its Belgian plant at Genk.
The company has already warned that it sees no sign of improvement in UK new
car demand and 'no indication of any real recovery before mid 1993.'
It has also lowered sales forecasts for several other markets including
Italy, Spain and France. Mr Ian McAllister, chairman of Ford of Britain,
yesterday welcomed the cut in UK interest rates as 'a prudent first step'.
The reduction should 'help to stabilise consumer confidence after the
turbulence of last week', he said. Further cuts would be welcome if they
could be achieved 'without triggering too rapid a fall in sterling'.
Ford's assembly plants at Dagenham, Essex, and Halewood, Merseyside,
together with its Southampton van plant, have been on short-time working for
much of the time since the summer shutdown. The plants will in effect move
to three-day weeks next month.
Ford of Britain said yesterday that about 10,000 workers in the UK would be
affected by the cuts next month which would reduce production by about
12,000 vehicles.
For four weeks from the end of this month, Ford will work a four-day week at
its Halewood plant, which produces the Escort-Orion range, by eliminating
the single Friday shift. There will be no output in the final week of
October.
At the Dagenham plant, which produces the Fiesta and which has been
exporting more than half of its output, the plant will be on a three-day
week for five weeks from next Monday.
In the UK, Rover has also introduced a four-day week on its Rover 200/400
assembly line at its plant in Longbridge, Birmingham, until the week
beginning October 26, cutting production by 7,000 cars. Mini and Metro lines
are on a three-day week until November, cutting output by 4,000 cars.
</TEXT>
