<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / Abu Dhabi issues documents in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE government of Abu Dhabi, the majority shareholder of the collapsed Bank
of Credit and Commerce In-ternational, said yesterday that it had released
19,000 important BCCI documents to US investigators and had invited US
officials to visit Abu Dhabi in the next two months.
The pledge of co-operation - which Congressional critics claimed was part of
a public-relations campaign by Abu Dhabi aimed at deflecting past criticism
 -comes days before the expected publication of a long BCCI report by
Senator John Kerry, the Massachusetts Democrat who has led Senate
investigations into the collapsed bank.
Abu Dhabi is also keen to make its case ahead of the publication of Lord
Justice Bingham's BCCI report in the UK.
However, the government of Abu Dhabi is not giving the BCCI documents to US
investigators. It is merely allowing the authorities to view the documents,
which are being held at the Washington Embassy of the United Arab Emirates.
Photocopies will not be permitted.
Among those who had previously claimed that Abu Dhabi had failed to provide
adequate co-operation in the BCCI case were the offices of Mr Kerry and of
Mr Robert Morgenthau, the Manhattan district attorney who last year brought
fraud charges against the bank.
Although Abu Dhabi has claimed it was 'the single biggest victim' of the
BCCI fraud, it is understood that its role has been under investigation by
Mr Morgenthau's office. Robinson, Lake, Lerer &amp; Montgomery, the Washington
public-relations firm that speaks for Abu Dhabi, said the documents were
being made available to officials of the US Department of Justice, the
Federal Reserve Board and the office of Mr Morgenthau.
Senator Kerry criticised Abu Dhabi's use of Robinson Lake in March because
Mr James Lake is also deputy manager of the campaign for the re-election of
President George Bush.
Senator Kerry has called on President Bush to dismiss Mr Lake, who serves as
a US adviser to the Abu Dhabi Investment Authority, one of the key
investment vehicles used by Sheikh Zayed Sultan Nahyan to retain majority
control of BCCI.
Mr Lake's office dismissed Senator Kerry's criticism as 'election-year
politics' yesterday and denied that there was any conflict of interest in Mr
Lake's helping to manage the Bush campaign while being paid to represent
BCCI's biggest shareholder.
</TEXT>
