FT  23 SEP 92 / Labour calls for banking review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LABOUR party called for a thorough review of banking regulations
yesterday once the results of the inquiries into last year's collapse of the
Bank of Credit and Commerce International (BCCI) are published.
A 600-page US Senate report on the BCCI affair is due to be published today
and is expected to be sharply critical of the role of the Bank of England.
A report by Lord Bingham into whether BCCI was supervised properly by the
Bank and the government is now likely to be published in the week beginning
October 19, when parliament reassembles for normal sittings - well after the
date originally set for publication.
It, too, is expected to be critical of the Bank's performance. Mr Norman
Lamont, the chancellor, is to make a statement to MPs when the report, or as
much of it as possible, is published. The government has consistently said
it will not make public any part of the report that might prejudice criminal
trials.
Yesterday's move by Labour is an attempt to ensure that even if the Treasury
is not heavily censured by the Bingham report, ministers do not escape all
responsibility for the affair. It also forms a further element in the
opposition's attack on Mr John Major's record as chancellor before he became
prime minister.
Labour claims that when Mr Major answered an emergency question on the
inquiry in July last year, he promised to report personally to the Commons.
'I shall publish the inquiry and then answer for it before this House,' the
prime minister said then.
'Mr Major has hidden behind Mr Lamont for far too long: it is high time he
learnt to carry the can.
'We will not stand for his ducking behind Mr Lamont yet again,' Mr Alistair
Darling, an opposition treasury spokesman, said yesterday.
He said that confidence in the UK banking system had been severely eroded.
Ministers should immediately set in motion a review of the working of the
Banking Act 1987, to ensure that 'regulation under the Bank is not a paper
exercise but provides a guarantee of effective regulation and protection for
customers and investors alike'.
</TEXT>
